<TITLE> Texas carries out 19th execution of 2007 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 HOUSTON, July 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Texas on Tuesday executed a man convicted of killing two teenagers who gave him a ride from a store near Houston in 1990. Lonnie Earl Johnson, 44, was the 19th man executed in Texas this year and the 398th since the state resumed the practice in 1982 after the US Supreme Court lifted a moratorium. Prosecutors said Johnson killed Gunar Fulk, 16, and Leroy McCaffrey, 17, after approaching them at a Tomball, Texas, store one night in August 1990 and asking for a ride. Johnson said he acted in self-defense after the boys attacked him for racial reasons. He was black. They were white. Jurors and appeals courts rejected his claim. Johnson was executed by lethal injection in Huntsville, Texas, with his mother, two friends and relatives of the victims among witnesses. He made no last meal request. In his last statement, he thanked loved ones there. "Take care. Give everybody my regards. I love you, and I'll see you in eternity. Father take me home. I am ready to go," he said. According to police and prosecutors, Johnson forced the two teenagers from Fulk's truck at gunpoint, shot them and stole the truck. Their bodies were found four miles from the store. The case attracted attention outside Texas because Johnson claimed a racial attack. Johnson said Fulk and McCaffrey threatened him with a pistol and were shot in a strugg
